  <p>The history of Philippine gaming reform is, mostly, the history of bills that did not pass. Senate Bill 2580 belongs near the top of that list. Filed in the previous Congress with substantial reformist ambition, it would have done much of what Senate Bill 2814 is now attempting &mdash; separate PAGCOR's regulatory function from its operator function, modernize the licensing framework, and bring the agency's structure in line with international gaming regulator best practice.</p>

  <p>It did not pass. It did not even advance to a floor vote. Eighteen months after the 19th Congress adjourned, SB 2580 is a footnote, mentioned in policy briefs but no longer in active legislative play. The current SB 2814 has taken its place &mdash; <a href="/articles/pagcor-privatization-bill.html">covered in our reporting on the bill's Senate committee advancement</a> &mdash; and the question that reform observers should be asking is what the new bill learned from the failure of the old one.</p>

